In this session, we will learn how to create models in which the dependent variable is categorical.

There are several ways in which the relationship between categorical variables can be analyzed. The most important concept to keep in mind is that we won’t be able to compute basic operations such as the mean. Instead, we will consider frequencies or counts of instances in each level of the variables.

See the following contingency table



We have 5 categorical variables here:

  • Book: Quijote
  • Subject: overt
  • Order: SV / VS
  • Animacy: animate / inanimate
  • Information Status: given / new


In this corpus data set, we are interested in knowing whether overt pre-verbal subjects (SV) have a tendency to be animate and to represent given information, as shown by other studies.

First, which are the DV and IV here?

Answer Correct:

  • DV: Order (SV/VS)
  • IV: Animacy (animate/inanimate) and Info.Status (given/new)


Second, we will examine each variable separately. Let’s visualize them, what are the tends we observe?

Answer Correct:

  • SV tends to be animate while VS tends to be inanimate
  • SV tends to be given information while VS tends to be new information


Now, the first an simplest test that we can perform with categorical variables is the chi-square test, which analyzes the relationship between two categorical variables. To put it simply, this test compares the frequencies observed in certain categories to the frequencies we might expect to get in those categories by chance. Thus, what we’ll be testing is if the rows and columns in a contingency table are significantly associated.


Assumptions

In statistical analysis, all parametric tests assume some certain characteristic about the data, also known as assumptions. Violation of these assumptions changes the conclusion of the research and interpretation of the results.

In the case of Chi-square:

  • The data points must be independent; cannot be used with repeated measures.
  • The frequencies in each cell must be greater than 5; we need a large sample.


How to conduct a Chi-square test

First, we will transform all variables into factors using the as.factor() function.

Then, we create a contingency table with the two factors we want to test significance for. We will use the CrossTable() function in the package gmodels

Animacy:

tbl1 <- table(cdata$Order, cdata$Animacy)
CrossTable(tbl1, fisher= T, chisq = T, expected = T, sresid= T)

Let’s break down these outputs:

The output produced by R first shows the contingency table in a very similar fashion to what we’d see in Goldvarb. For each combination of Order and Animacy (animate/inanimate) or Info.Status (given/new) we see:

  • the number of observations
  • the expected frequency
  • the chi-square contribution of the cell
  • the row proportion
  • the column proportion
  • the total proportion
  • the standardized residual.

Next we have the actual Chi-square results. The tests’ output indicates that the row and column variables are statistically significantly associated for Animacy and Information Status.Thus, the tests confirm that what we saw in the bar plots we graphed is statistically significant.

Finally, the output shows the sample estimate odds ratio, indicating the effects size. Effect size is a quantitative measure of the magnitude of the experimental effect. The larger the effect size the stronger the relationship between two variables. You can look at the effect size when comparing any two groups to see how substantially different they are. Odds ratios measure how many times bigger the odds of one outcome is for one value of an IV, compared to another value.

We see that the odds ratio is highly significant and not equal to 1, which is what we’d want because this is the point at which the direction of the effect changes. In this case, the odds of SV are greater when the subject is animate or given.


Binary Logistic Regression

So far our focus has been on describing interactions or associations between two categorical variables mostly via single summary statistics and with significance testing, as well as by looking at the variables separately. We will now focus on a special class of models known as the binary logistic regression.

Binary Logistic Regression is a special type of regression where a binary response variable is related to a set of explanatory variables, which can be discrete and/or continuous.

Linear regression is not capable of predicting probability. If you use linear regression to model a binary response variable, for example, the resulting model may not restrict the predicted Y values within 0 and 1, as shown below. Here’s where logistic regression comes into play, where you get a probability score that reflects the probability of the occurrence at the event.

In logistic regression, the Probability or Odds of the response taking a particular value is modeled based on combination of values taken by the predictors. More formally, the equation models the logit-transformed probability as a linear relationship with the predictor variables. In our case, we will use logistic regression to model the probability that subject-verb order belongs to a particular category, SV or VS [Pr(SV-order = SV/VS)].


Assumptions

  • the dependent variable has a binomial distribution. The binomial distribution is a probability distribution that summarizes the likelihood that a value will take one of two independent values under a given set of parameters or assumptions.
  • the errors are normally distributed and independent.
  • does not assume a linear relationship between DV and IVs.


Visualization

Let’s create our model:

 model1 <-  glm(Order ~ Animacy + Info.Status, family= binomial, data=cdata)
 summary(model1)

Before we read this output, there are three concepts we need to understand:

  • Probability: ranges from 0-1;for example, a event might have a .8 success probability.

  • Odds: range from 0 and positive infinity; defined, for example, as the ratio of the probability of success over the probability of failure, then 8/.2 = 4. That is to say that the odds of success are 4 to 1.

  • Log-odds: the transformation from odds to log of odds is the log transformation, and it ranges from negative infinity to positive infinity. We transform probability into log-odds because it is usually difficult to model a variable which has restricted range.


1. Deviance

Deviance is a measure of goodness of fit of a generalized linear model, higher numbers indicate worse fit.

The null deviance shows how well the response variable is predicted by a model that includes only the intercept (grand mean) and the residual deviance includes all predictors.


2. Fisher’s Scoring Iterations

For our model, we see that Fisher’s Scoring Algorithm needed 5 iterations to perform the fit.


3. Coefficients

A. Estimates: These are the values for the logistic regression equation for predicting the dependent variable from the independent variable. They are in log-odds units.

B. Std. Err: These are the standard errors associated with the coefficients. The standard error is used for testing whether the parameter is significantly different from 0.

C. z and P>|z|: These columns provide the z-value and 2-tailed p-value used in testing the null hypothesis that the coefficient (parameter) is 0.


As a final step let’s interpret the Estimates:

The Estimates ina logistic regression model tell you about the relationship between the independent variables and the dependent variable, where the dependent variable is on the logit scale. These estimates tell the amount of increase in the predicted log odds of Order that would be predicted by a 1 unit increase in the predictor, holding all other predictors constant

Because these coefficients are in log-odds units, they are often difficult to interpret, so they are often converted into odds ratios or back into probabilities. Here, we will do he latter.

1. Dependent variable: when we used CrossTable to perform Chi-Square tests, we were provided a distribution table (similar to Goldvarb) and saw that thre freuency of VS (57) was higher than SV (43). We need to take this into account when interpreting our estimates.

2. Intercept: The intercept here is a combination of the reference level for our two IVs, therefore it is animate given. From our tables and graphs, we know that VS tends not to be animate-given, let’s see if the model confirms this. Indeed, according to the model the log-odds of animate-given with VS are significantly negative, indicating a negative likelihood of this combination of factors. However, how improbable is it? We can use a """"“simple”"""" equation to convert the logg-odds into probabilities and make this estimate more interpretable: p= exp(2.469) / (1 + exp(2.569)) -> p= 0.846 / 1.0846 -> p= 0.07 This means that VS only has .7% chances of being animate-given.

3. Predictors For Animacy-Inanimate and Info.Status-New, we see that both of them are significantly positive, indicating a positive likelihood of VS being inanimate and new.

We can apply the same formula as above to obtain their probabilities BUT we first need to add the intercept to these estimates, since what we are trying to interpret is how they relate to this reference value.

  • Animacy-Inanimate: -2.469 + 2.863 = 0.367 -> p= 0.59

  • Info.Status-New: -2.469 + 2.228 = -0.241 -> p= 0.43

Thus, VS has a 59% probability of being inanimate and a 43% probability of being new.

In all, these numbers together with our distribution tables and graphs paint a clear picture where post-verbal subjects have a tendency to be inanimate and new, whereas pre-verbal subjects tend to be animate and given.
